@node Browsing entries
@section Browsing entries

@findex pass-extras-open-at-point
When you are reviewing your password entries in a @samp{pass-mode} buffer, you may want to log in to the associated website. The command @code{pass-extras-open-at-point} combines two steps into one: it copies the password of the entry at point to the kill ring (via @code{pass-copy}) and then opens the URL stored in the entry's @samp{password-store-url-field} in your default browser. If the entry does not contain a URL field, the command signals an error.

@findex pass-extras-insert-generated-no-symbols
The command @code{pass-extras-insert-generated-no-symbols} creates a new password store entry with a randomly generated password that contains only alphanumeric characters (no special symbols). It delegates to @code{password-store-generate-no-symbols} for the actual generation and then refreshes the @samp{pass-mode} buffer so the new entry appears immediately.

@node Generating passwords
@section Generating passwords

@findex pass-extras-generate-password
Sometimes you need a password without creating a new entry in the store, for instance when filling a form in a browser or registering for a service you do not intend to save. The command @code{pass-extras-generate-password} prompts you to choose a password type from several categories provided by the @samp{password-generator} package:

@itemize
@item
Simple (alphanumeric)
@item
Strong (with special characters)
@item
Numeric (PIN)
@item
Phonetic (memorable)
@item
Words (correct horse battery style)
@item
Custom (your own alphabet)
@end itemize

The generated password is copied to the kill ring and will be automatically cleared after the number of seconds specified by @code{password-store-time-before-clipboard-restore}, just like a regular @samp{pass} copy operation. This ensures that generated passwords do not linger in the clipboard.

@node Key management
@section Key management

@findex pass-extras-store-key
@findex pass-extras-export-key
Cryptographic key files (SSH keys, GPG keys, API tokens stored in files) can be imported into the password store for safekeeping. The command @code{pass-extras-store-key} prompts for a key file and a target entry name, then pipes the file contents into @samp{pass insert --multiline} to store them as a multiline entry. Completion is offered for existing entry names.

The reverse operation is provided by @code{pass-extras-export-key}, which prompts for an existing entry (with completion requiring a match) and a destination file path, then writes the entry contents to that file. This is useful when you need to restore a key file on a new machine.

@node Git-crypt integration
@section Git-crypt integration

@findex pass-extras-git-crypt-unlock
If you store @samp{git-crypt} symmetric keys in @samp{pass}, the command @code{pass-extras-git-crypt-unlock} can unlock a repository without ever writing the key to disk. It prompts for a @samp{pass} entry containing the key (with completion) and runs @samp{git-crypt unlock} with process substitution so the key is fed directly from @samp{pass} into @samp{git-crypt}. The command operates in the current @code{default-directory} unless an optional REPO argument is provided programmatically. It reports success or failure in the echo area.

